ted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume demonstrates how, from the beginning of the Atlantic slave trade, enslaved and free Africans in the Americas used Catholicism and Christian-derived celebrations as spaces for autonomous cultural expression, social organization, and political empowerment. Their appropriation of Catholic-based celebrations calls into question the long-held idea that Africans and their descendants in the diaspora either resignedly accepted Christianity or else transformed its religious rituals into syncretic objects of stealthy resistance.In cities and on plantations throughout the Americas, men and women of African birth or descent staged mock battles against heathens, elected Christian queens and kings with great pageantry, and gathered in festive rituals to express their devotion to saints. Many of these traditions endure in the twenty-first century. The contributors to this volume draw connections between these Afro-Catholic festivals-observed from North America to South America and the Caribbean-and their precedents in the early modern kingdom of Kongo, one of the main regions of origin of men and women enslaved in the New World. This transatlantic perspective offers a useful counterpoint to the Yoruba focus prevailing in studies of African diasporic religions and reveals how Kongo-infused Catholicism constituted a site for the formation of black Atlantic tradition.Afro-Catholic Festivals in the Americas complicates the notion of Christianity as a European tool of domination and enhances our comprehension of the formation and trajectory of black religious culture on the American continent. It will be of great interest to scholars of African diaspora, religion, Christianity, and performance.In addition to the editor, the contributors include Kevin Dawson, Jeroen Dewulf, Junia Ferreira Furtado, Michael Iyanaga, Dianne M. Stewart, Miguel A. Valerio, and Lisa Voigt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aAfricanszAmericaxReligion. 0aBlackszAmericaxReligion. 0aFasts and feastszAmericaxCatholic Church. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aDawson, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewulf, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira Furtado, Junia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFromont, Cécile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFromont, Cécile, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIyanaga, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Dianne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValerio, Miguel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoigt, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271084367zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271084367423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271084367.jpg  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK